# Workspace Rules

## Documentation Discipline (CRITICAL)

**Documentation is not optional. It is a core part of the development process.**

- Read `docs/implementation/` before making any non-trivial changes
- Update documentation BEFORE implementing changes to data models, flows, or APIs
- Documentation must stay in sync with code at all times
- Treat outdated documentation as a critical bug
- See `docs-discipline.mdc` for detailed requirements

## Environment Variables

- Never commit `.env.local` or `.env` files
- Document required environment variables in code comments or README
- Use descriptive variable names with clear prefixes (e.g., `DATABASE_URL`, `NEXT_PUBLIC_*`)
- Validate environment variables at application startup
- Provide sensible defaults for development where appropriate

## Git Workflow

- Use descriptive commit messages following conventional commits format
- Keep commits focused on a single feature or fix
- Create feature branches for significant changes
- Keep main/master branch deployable at all times
- Include documentation updates in the same commit as code changes

## Development Workflow

- Run `prisma generate` after schema changes
- Run `npm run lint` before committing
- Test tRPC endpoints during development using tRPC client
- Use TypeScript strict mode - fix type errors, don't suppress them
- Keep Prisma schema and migrations in sync

## Code Quality

- **Type Safety**: Prefer explicit types over `any`, use `unknown` when type is truly unknown
- **Error Handling**: Always handle errors explicitly, use AppError for user-facing errors
- **Null Safety**: Use optional chaining and nullish coalescing appropriately
- **Async/Await**: Prefer async/await over promises chains
- **Imports**: Use absolute imports with `@/` prefix
- **Exports**: Use named exports over default exports for better tree-shaking

## Performance

- Use React Server Components where possible
- Implement proper loading states and error boundaries
- Optimize database queries (use Prisma select to limit fields)
- Use TanStack Query caching effectively
- Consider pagination for large data sets
- Monitor bundle size and optimize imports

## Security

- Never log sensitive data (private keys, passwords, tokens)
- Validate all user inputs with Zod schemas
- Use parameterized queries (Prisma handles this)
- Implement proper authentication checks in protected procedures
- Sanitize user inputs before database operations
- Keep dependencies up to date for security patches

## Testing

- Write unit tests for service functions
- Test tRPC routers with test clients
- Mock external dependencies (Solana RPC, database)
- Test error cases, not just happy paths
- Keep test files co-located with source files or in `__tests__` directories

## Documentation

- Document complex business logic in code comments
- Keep README files updated with setup instructions
- Document API changes when adding new tRPC procedures
- Add JSDoc comments for public service functions
- Document environment variables needed for each feature

## Dependencies

- Keep dependencies up to date, but test before upgrading major versions
- Prefer well-maintained packages with active communities
- Avoid adding unnecessary dependencies
- Review bundle size impact of new dependencies
- Use exact versions for critical dependencies in production

## Database

- Always use migrations for schema changes, never direct SQL in production
- Do not create migration files manually; use Prisma migrate commands
- Test migrations on a copy of production data when possible
- Keep migrations small and focused
- Document breaking changes in migration files
- Backup database before running migrations in production

## Solana Integration

- Handle network errors and retries gracefully
- Use connection pooling for RPC calls
- Implement proper transaction error handling
- Validate transaction signatures before processing
- Consider rate limiting for RPC endpoints
- Use proper error types for Solana-specific errors

## When in Doubt

- **Read the documentation first** — check `docs/implementation/` for existing patterns
- Prefer type safety over convenience
- Keep business logic in services, not in routers or components
- Use existing patterns from the codebase
- Ask for clarification rather than making assumptions
- Update documentation when you discover gaps or outdated information
